			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2632">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Enclosed is my one-year subscription payment. If I had the money for a lifetime subscription, I&rsquo;d send it. I can&rsquo;t believe how much of my own unpredictable life story is being told in your magazine, which I now think of as &ldquo;our&rdquo; magazine. In every issue I read about things that trouble, awe, inspire, upset, and tickle me, as well as make me wonder.</p>

<p>The September 1997 issue, however, made me so angry I nearly canceled my subscription. &ldquo;<a href="/article/1893">Eric, Recovering Wino</a>,&rdquo; by Eric Granskou, reminded me of my past and shook my present reality, even after the emotions it triggered eased. People who don&rsquo;t know what it&rsquo;s like to be an addict or an alcoholic get a very distorted view from accounts like Granskou&rsquo;s. His story is only part of the picture. People ought to know, too, that addicts and alcoholics are notorious liars who will go to any lengths to tell tales about themselves. They will also go to any lengths to change, to stay sober, and to live decent, fulfilling lives.</p>

<p>I&rsquo;m glad I didn&rsquo;t cancel, because today the current issue came in the mail. Keep doing what you do, so that we can continue to have &ldquo;our&rdquo; magazine.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">E. S. “Sami” Arvizu<br>Beverly Hills, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2359">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I&rsquo;ve been a subscriber for five years. A couple of years ago, I got bogged down in the dismal subject matter, particularly the essay by the homeless alcoholic who wrote of eating his own feces. [&ldquo;<a href="/article/1893">Eric, Recovering Wino</a>,&rdquo; by Eric Granskou, September 1997]. I felt ready to quit.</p>

<p>Then my boyfriend&rsquo;s brother called us from jail, again. His life had been one long struggle with alcohol and drugs, and his family had almost run out of forgiveness. So I showed my boyfriend the article. I <em>made</em> him read it. That night, he called his brother in jail with tears in his eyes and offered to help for the first time.</p>

<p>I think that is why I always renew my subscription. Because, no matter how hard it sometimes is to read, <em>The Sun</em> opens me up to the truth, not as it is portrayed in the media, but as it exists in the minds and hearts and lives of my fellow human beings.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Tamara Baren<br>Verdi, Nevada</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

